John","meanings":["Greek: the Lord gave graciously; whom Jehovah gave; whom Jehovah bestowed."]},{"name":"Jeane","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Jean ."]}]},{"name":"Ier","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["and Norwegian vernacular form of   Peter ."],"variants":[{"name":"Peter","meanings":["form of the name of the best-known of all Christ's apostles, traditionally regarded as the founder of the Christian Church. The name derives, via Latin, from Greek <i>petros</i> ‘stone, rock’. This is used as a translation of the Aramaic byname <i>Cephas</i>, given to the apostle  Simon  son of Jona, to distinguish him from another of the same name (  Simon Zelotes ). ‘When Jesus beheld him, he said, Thou art Simon the son of Jona: thou shalt be called Cephas, which is by interpretation, A stone’ (John 1:42). According to Matthew 16:17–18, Christ says more explicitly, ‘Blessed art thou, Simon Bar-jona … thou art Peter, and upon this rock I will build my church’. The name has been in continuous use since the Middle Ages."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Jean Ier was born about 1240, in Châteauvillain, Haute-Marne, Grand Est, France, his father, Simon Ier \"le jeune\" de Broyes de Chateauvillain, was 61 and his mother, Alix de Luzy, was 39. He married Jeanne de Semur-en-Brionnais before 1265. They were the parents of at least 2 sons and 2 daughters. He died in 1313, at the age of 74, and was buried in Châteauvillain, Haute-Marne, Grand Est, France."},"et":{"ABT 1240–1313":"umbes 1240–1313","1230–Female":"1230–Surnud","1240–1313":"1240–1313","1245–Female":"1245–Surnud","1250–1270":"1250–1270","1240–Female":"1240–Surnud","1255–1306":"1255–1306","1260–Female":"1260–Surnud","1264–1332":"1264–1332","1265–1288":"1265–1288","1180–1259":"1180–1259","1202–1270":"1202–1270","1264":"1264","1230":"1230","1240":"1240","1250":"1250","1260":"1260","1270":"1270","1180":"1180","ABT 1240":"umbes 1240","1259":"1259","1